## Key Design Decisions

**Serial webhook queue** — The webhook endpoint returns `200` immediately and processes events one at a time. GitLab never times out, and simultaneous multi-job failures don't create a thundering herd.

**Last-N-chars log truncation** — `getJobLog()` returns the *last* 8000 characters of a job log, not the first. Errors always appear at the tail, not buried in setup output. This directly improves LLM analysis quality.

**75% confidence gate on auto-patching** — The agent creates an issue on every failure, but only opens a patch MR when confidence ≥ 75%. This prevents noisy, incorrect MRs from eroding engineer trust.

**`Promise.allSettled` for all parallel fetches** — Every parallel operation (GitLab context, Fivetran enrichment) uses `allSettled` rather than `Promise.all`. A single 404 or timeout never aborts the entire analysis.

**Graceful degradation on every tool** — Every tool catches its own errors and returns mock data rather than throwing. The agent completes a full run — including a real GitLab issue — even with zero live credentials beyond the LLM.

**Arize as meta-layer** — Arize observes the agent itself, not the application. You can audit every root-cause decision, track confidence drift over time, and compare LLM accuracy against human-resolved incidents.

